on child growth of roundworm infections among preschool and school aged children in six nationally designated poor counties in china the data used in this paper were collected by the authors in april and june of 2010 as part of a wide scale survey in guizhou and sichuan provinces in the southwestern part of china our data indicate high rates of infection in the survey areas overall 21.2 percent of preschool aged children and 22.9 percent of elementary school aged children were infected with one or more of the three types of roundworms tested for in the survey ascaris lumbricoides ascariasis ancylostoma duodenale hookworm and trichuris trichuria whipworm these infection rates are high enough for the study areas to be considered moderate risk communities according to the world health organization using multivariate analysis we identify individual behavioral and household factors associated with roundworm infection including maternal education drinking unclean water and eating uncooked meat among others by using decomposition analysis we explain why worms pose a significant problem in some areas but not in others our results support the conclusions of existing research showing a statistically significant negative correlation between infection with intestinal worms and the physical development of children represented by weight for age and height for age z scores topics water china stanford university all rights reserved 650 723 2300 terms of use copyright complaints rss+ rss xml feeds
